Latent Variables

  • Variables that are not directly observed by rather inferred from other variables that are observed.
  • Examples:
    • Social class
    • Anxiety
    • Satisfaction

Latent Variables

  • Latent variables are often constructs (or concepts).
  • These are operationalized in surveys in the form of observable and measurable components.
  • For example, consider designing a survey. What would you want to learn? What would you ask?

Factor Analysis

  • Goal is to reduce a set of variables into a smaller set of factors.
  • FA vs. PCA: Emphasis on interpretability.
  • EFA vs. CFA: Start with data or start with theory?

EFA benefits

  • Reduce dimensions
  • Reduce uncertainty
  • Reduce data collection

EFA: nFactors package

  • Instead of finding the components that account, in descending order, for the most variance in the data (PCA), EFA finds solutions in which a small number of loadings for each factor are very high, while the rest are low.
  • The goal is to find interpretable solutions.

EFA: Uniqueness

  • The proportion of variability not explained by the factors
  • The higher a variable’s uniqueness, the less well the factors account for its variance
  • Ranges from 0 to 1
brand.fa$uniquenesses
##   perform    leader    latest       fun   serious   bargain     value    trendy 
## 0.6239890 0.3272841 0.0050000 0.7941232 0.5303783 0.3020242 0.2019618 0.5240309 
##     rebuy 
## 0.5753600

EFA: Communality

  • The proportion of variability that is explained by the factors
  • Equal to 1 - uniqueness
  • Also equal to the sum of the squared loadings
  • Ranges from 0 to 1
1 - brand.fa$uniquenesses
##   perform    leader    latest       fun   serious   bargain     value    trendy 
## 0.3760110 0.6727159 0.9950000 0.2058768 0.4696217 0.6979758 0.7980382 0.4759691 
##     rebuy 
## 0.4246400
apply(brand.fa$loadings^2, 1, sum)

EFA: Rotation choices

  • Should we force factors be uncorrelated?
  • If not, we can choose an oblique rotation
  • For example, install GPArotation package and try:
(brand.fa.ob <- factanal(brand.sc[, 1:9], factors=3, rotation="oblimin"))

EFA: Factor Scores

brand.fa.ob <- factanal(brand.sc[, 1:9],
                        factors=3,
                        rotation="oblimin",
                        scores="Bartlett")

brand.scores <- data.frame(brand.fa.ob$scores) 

brand.scores$brand <- brand.sc$brand 

head(brand.scores) 
##      Factor1    Factor2    Factor3 brand
## 1  1.6521364 -0.6886749  0.5256104     a
## 2 -1.4005333 -1.6681901 -0.6764121     a
## 3  1.1457311 -1.0618008 -0.4285853     a

## 5  2.0002009 -1.9071519 -0.4559905     a
## 6  1.4175063  0.3339462  0.8555525     a
brand.fa.mean <- aggregate(. ~ brand,
                           data=brand.scores,
                           mean)

rownames(brand.fa.mean) <- brand.fa.mean[, 1] # brand names 

brand.fa.mean <- brand.fa.mean[, -1]

names(brand.fa.mean) <- c("Leader", "Value", "Latest") # factor names

CFA

  • We often start with a set of constructs and we want to test how well they are captured by operationalized variables
  • This is done frequently when designing surveys
